1. What is a Functional Interface?

	A Functional Interface in Java is an interface that contains only one abstract method.
	It can also have multiple default and static methods, but only one method without a body.
	Functional interfaces are mainly used with Lambda Expressions to write shorter and more readable code.
	Java provides the @FunctionalInterface annotation to declare such interfaces. Examples include Runnable, Callable, and Comparator.
	They are widely used in Java 8 features like Stream API.

2. What is the for-each loop used for?

	The for-each loop is used to iterate through elements of arrays or collections in Java.
	It allows programmers to access each element directly without using an index variable.
	This makes the code simpler, cleaner, and easier to understand. The loop automatically moves from one element to the next until all elements are processed.
	It is commonly used with arrays, ArrayList, and other collection classes. It reduces the chance of index-related errors.

3. What is the difference between break and continue?

	The break statement is used to terminate the loop immediately and transfer control outside the loop.
	It can also be used inside a switch statement.
	The continue statement skips the current iteration of the loop and moves to the next iteration.
	It does not terminate the loop completely.
	Break stops the loop entirely, while continue only skips one cycle.
	Both are used to control the flow of loops.

4. Explain if-else and switch statements.

	The if-else statement is used for decision making based on conditions. 
	If the condition is true, the if block executes; otherwise, the else block executes. 
	It is commonly used when checking ranges or multiple logical conditions. 
	The switch statement is used to select one block of code from multiple options based on a variable value. 
	It uses case labels and usually includes a break statement to stop further execution. 
	Switch works with types like int, char, String, and enum.

5. What is an enhanced for loop?

	An enhanced for loop is another name for the for-each loop introduced in Java 5. 
	It is used to traverse arrays and collections easily without using an index variable. 
	The loop automatically retrieves each element one by one. 
	It improves code readability and reduces complexity. 
	However, it is mainly used for reading elements, not for modifying them. 
	It is widely used when working with collections and arrays.